column1: 70105;instagram;2019-01-19 09:20:33;FALSE;"to all people out there struggling with #ptsd :
it's been four month now since i absolved my last therapy. it was the first time i learned about ptbs and the symptomes. it's not like i didn't feel them earlier
column2: but in the therapy i had the chance to learn that i am not suffering alone. ptbs is a serious disorder and there are so many people out there suffering without anyone to talk to about their feelings. about worst nightmares
column3: highest amount of fear and fighting against it. there also will be people
column4: that will call you a psychopath. people who don't or don't want to understand what you have been through and that you survived biggest pain - most people luckily couldn't even imagine. you are way more then a diagnose and you are worth to love and forgive yourself! never ever (!!) let anyone tell you
column5: you wouldn't be worth it and that you are hopeless
column6: manipulative or anything else. please get rid of those toxic people in your life. they will destroy you
column7: even if they are the people you love the most. you are not alone! every time i met someone with ptbs or trauma experience
column8: i felt the unconditionally solidarity between us. never stop talking about what happend. never give up yourself and the most important thing: never let toxic people tell you
column9: you wouldn't be worth anything. you are more then that. never give up growing. i love you.

column1: 70319;instagram;2019-01-19 03:21:28;FALSE;"men are vulnerable. we’re taught that we’re not supposed to be
column2: but we are. we’re vulnerable to heartache
column5: and so on. but male vulnerability is often equated with weakness
column6: which in turn is associated with shame. so why would a man decidedly make himself vulnerable to get the help he needs? how does a man know when vulnerability is no longer a weakness but a strength? who makes that determination? that very shame associated with being vulnerable is exactly why suicide is the leading cause of death in men under 50. working with teen boys
column8: trying to redefine what it means to be vulnerable to young men who’ve already been brainwashed to believe that silence and violence are the only two acceptable responses to hardships in life. i see their pain
column9: their desire to break through and reach out
column10: and the shame that holds them back. men suffer too. our mental health matters. it’s time we break through the barriers of shame for ourselves and for the next generation who watches us so closely.

column2: it is still our reality as women to face workplace challenges like lack of respect
column5: simply because we are women.  and if you work in a male dominated industry

column2: i showed up to board meetings with a game face on continually proving that i deserve to be there - whereas respect is inherently earned by the males. i can’t even begin to count the number of times i’ve been called “darling” and “honey
column3: ” or assumptions were made that i wasn’t in a leadership role. -

column1: i was actually told from an investor that because i’m “creative” i can’t be successful in growing a large business.  what?  who says?  why can’t i be both?  because i’m a woman? -
their sexist attitudes added to my insecurities i was already battling
column2: but i was determined to prove them wrong and open their minds.  i hustled like nobody’s business and could have killed myself trying to prove my worth and value to them. -

column1: what i learned is that while we may not be able to change the perception of men like this
column2: we can change our outlook.  i know i kicked ass in my business.  as women
column3: we need to stop being modest.  our work ethic and relationship building skills are our weapons.  and i used them frequently building my business. -

column2: we don’t need to be like a man.  we need to celebrate what makes us unique
column3: embrace our strong points and shine.  xo  #youglowgirl #glowtogether

column1: 70447;instagram;2019-01-19 01:05:50;FALSE;"“i’m addressing you publicly today as a final step and statement to myself that i have nothing to be ashamed of.” kyle stephens

column2: kyle stephens was the first survivor to face larry nassar at his sentencing hearing. if you don’t know kyle’s story
column3: you need to hear it.  kyle wasn’t a gymnast.  kyle
column5: was abused by someone she knew and trusted
column6: someone her family knew and trusted
column8: her abuse happened right in her own home.  and like so many children
column9: she wasn’t believed – that is until she met detective andrea munford and prosecutor angela povilaitis. they believed her
column10: and because kyle was the only non-medical victim to come forward
column11: they were able to get a search warrant for nassar’s house that lead to a discovery of child pornography that eventually lead to a predator being stopped.  kyle’s story is important for so many reasons
column12: and i wrote a blog about the three things i want parents to know. you can read it here ➡️ https://thethirdchild.org/2019/01/18/one-year-later-what-we-can-learn-from-survivors/

column2: know what to do if the unimaginable happens
column3: and protect and defend the child

70455;instagram;2019-01-19 00:06:11;FALSE;"lets throw it back to an episode from the fall where we talked to @enlivensarah. this is a great episode because it showcases how much (or how little) you can do to be an activist mom. you can get involved or you can work on the ""small scale"" like teaching consent - which really would have giant results.
sarah beaulieu is an expert at engaging men in conversations about sexual harassment and violence and founder of the uncomfortable conversation
column2: a nonprofit organization that produces short-form videos to normalize conversations about consent
column4: advocacy and supporting survivors of sexual violence.

column2: we talked about: • the graphic mentioned in the interview: the truth about false accusation • ny times article link mentioned in the interview here • sarah’s perspective on the #metoo movement • teaching kids about consent in a playground context and respecting kids’ personal space • the fluency around how to navigate your own body and relationship to someone else’s body • the importance of practicing uncomfortable conversations & nancy’s uncomfortable conversation earlier in the week.";;en;#MeToo;@enlivensarah.;;;;0;;losethecape;Lose The Cape Podcast;;0;False;2;0;0;27;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/7be449d1733dfacecaea71339801d1ee/5D03E283/t51.2885-15/e35/50184494_2052943071453697_5978757482978411186_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"lets throw it back to an episode from the fall where we talked to @enlivensarah. this is a great episode because it showcases how much (or how little) you can do to be an activist mom. you can get involved or you can work on the ""small scale"" like teaching consent - which really would have giant results.

column1: via @rollingstone: r. kelly and his label

column1: 70477;instagram;2019-01-19 00:19:28;FALSE;"you see this ""to do"" list...it may not look like much but for me this was a huge accomplishment!  since the attack my short term memory as well as my energy level has been shot!  i can't always remember what it is i need to do or am wanting to do and when i can remember i don't always have the energy to complete the task...not to mention if there are multiple tasks i can become easily overwhelmed...all symptoms of truama related ptsd!
but yestersay... yesterday i not only remembered my tasks for the day
column2: i completed them with help from my husband lol.  i even managed to go out into the world and people then came home and completed my tasks!  it's a big win for me no matter how small and i'll take it!

column6: make up the wealthiest group of black men and women on the planet. “archon” means “demon” – the kind that like to keep hidden.

column1: 70510;instagram;2019-01-18 23:33:18;FALSE;"let’s get real with whyt again. warning
if you were to look at my instagram profile earlier last year
column2: it would have looked like i was in a happy
column4: relationship with a boyfriend. little did you know
column5: that i was being sexually and mentally abused while also suffering with extreme anxiety and depression. earlier this year
column6: i shared my #nofilter story via video telling my mental illness story. now i am choosing to take off yet another filter of my story. i was raped
column8: and abused. as i am healing from this trauma
column9: i have become passionate about being an advocate for abuse and mental illness. i want to make clear my intentions of sharing this. i am not sharing out of spite
column11: or attention. the details of who and what are not important. i’m more concerned about speaking up for those victims like myself. i am doing this for the girl that i once was who was so lost
column13: and living such dark things. i am choosing to take back my power and use it to empower. i cannot stay silent. i will make my voice heard. the world is ignorant regarding abusive relationships and victims of rape and sexual assault but i’m here to change that

column1: check the link in my bio to watch my part two #nofilter video about my experiences regarding my abuse. #metoo
and stay tuned for my podcast launch where i will continue sharing my journey and insights.

column1: 70634;instagram;2019-01-18 22:03:07;FALSE;"it is a sad state of affairs that women walking alone at night must worry for their safety. not only at night but even during the day. .

if i’m walking somewhere and there are no other people around my senses go on “alert”. i put my mindfulness into my peripheral vision. i toss my hair to give me a chance to nonchalantly look over my shoulder without seeming to do so
column2: and check there’s no danger lurking. i’ll put my keys between my fingers to get ready to use them as a weapon. i’ll get out my phone and call someone to ensure i’m connected to another person or get ready with the keypad to dial 000 quickly if i need to. and it’s probably 2-3 times per week i’m in a potential situation like this (without even taking any real risks! just as part of every day life.) luckily i’ve never had to truly defend myself like this. but as we have seen in the case of aiia maasarwe in melbourne this week
column3: brutally attacked and killed while on the phone to her sister
column4: while walking home from the tram
column5: apparently all this is even not enough. .

column1: what on earth do we do about this? my friends and any #goodmen in sydney with a #martialarts background @brenfosterreal @mentalistphoenix @shauno_connor or any #sydney #martialartsgirls - is there any way for a woman who is not an athlete or martial artist to deflect and wound or stall an attacker sufficient to put them out of action long enough to get time to run away?
if any of you were interested in running an event for this as a public service to help protect women i would help promote it. (and attend!).
societal change is needed such that we don’t need these skills... but that sort of change takes time... in the mean time
column2: smart effective self defense is clearly a life skill that we all (unfortunately) need. i don’t want to live in fear expecting the worst
column3: so how do we do this in a positive way? feeling sad in this moment that this question is even necessary. .

column1: the 3rd annual women’s march la is happening this saturday

column4: followed by speakers at 9am for around an hour. at 10am

column7: organizers are asking attendees to register in advance to give them an idea of how many people to expect. let’s protest peacefully folks! ✊🏻🙌🏻💕💪 .

column2: i know it’s been a while. i have a story for you but i also just wanted to remind you all that if you ever have any stories to share feel free to message me

i was on an afternoon walk in town. a car pulled over and rolled its window down. i stopped and looked into the car (maybe they were asking for directions?) only to find a man grinning and eyeing me up and down. y’all know that feeling? the gross one that makes you feel like nothing more than an object? yeah

column1: the man was saying things to me
column2: but i started walking away as fast as possible. he followed behind me
column3: slowly rolling along the curb side while i fumbled around with my phone. i called my dad—just so that i could be on the phone with someone. when my dad picked up i immediately started bawling. after being on the phone
column4: the car disappeared and i walked as fast as possible back home

column1: nothing really came of the situation
column2: but i still couldn’t shake that terrible sinking feeling of seeing the man and knowing exactly what he was thinking. sometimes i feel like i should only leave my house if i look gross.. so that i could go about my day not worrying about things like this. then again

70773;instagram;2019-01-18 20:03:32;FALSE;it’s okay to say no to things and it’s perfectly fine to try new things too.
it’s been hard learning to trust myself. and it’s not always easy. i severed ties with my grandparents over the summer. i used to try so hard to visit them
column2: and every time i saw them
column3: they would bring up her. most of the times it was to tell me how embarrassed they were of me. i left their house in tears 3 times before i decided i needed to trust myself and do what was right for my soul. it was one of the hardest decisions have ever i made.

column1: and my father called me recently to let me know that my grandfather just had a stroke. i am being pulled in so many directions on how to best handle this situation. i know i’ll never receive an apology and i don’t know that i even want one. it bothers me most knowing that when i do reach out
column2: my family will act as if nothing has been wrong this whole time.

column1: so instead of doing what my family has always done
column2: i’m going to trust myself to make the right choice. at the end of the day
column3: i’m not responsible for anyone’s feelings but my own. and i can’t just follow along with these unspoken rules my family wants me to adhere to. i don’t know what i’m going to do yet
column4: but i do know that i’ve been listening to myself to find out what i think the right decision is. #weareher

column1: 70794;instagram;2019-01-18 19:05:56;FALSE;"خب همون‌طور که ممکنه شنیده باشین، یه زمزمه هایی به وجود اومده مبنی بر این که این چالش ده سال قبل رو خود فیسبوک علم کرده برای بزرگتر  کردن مجموعه داده های خودش جهت تقویت الگوریتم های تشخیص چهره. به نظرتون این چقدر معتبره؟ اطلاعاتی در این زمینه دارین؟ نظرتون چیه؟ به نظر شما این نقض حریم شخصی افراد هست یا نه؟
و این که فکر میکنید در طول روز  با چه چیزای به  ظاهر ساده ای سر و کار داریم که ممکنه پشتش یه عالمه فکر و طرح و سیاست و برنامه ریزی باشه؟

column2: it reveals who you are.” michelle obama “so many of us go through life with our stories hidden. feeling ashamed or afraid when our truth doesn’t live up to some established ideal. we grow up with messages that tell us there is only one way to be american. that if our skin is darker
column4: or we don’t experience love in a particular way
column5: or we speak another language or come from another country then we don’t belong. that is until someone dares to start telling that story differently.” #michelleobama

column1: i had a busy morning with a photo shoot for a fitness clothing company 😍💪🏽 so my afternoon is being scrunched 😆 i headed to the gym for a quick but effective workout to get my sweat on and get back into the groove.

even though i just trekked 13 days in nepal to everest base camp i feel like i’m needing to build back up my strength as i embark on ironman training which *technically starts monday but since i got in the pool yesterday it’s already started 😂
when i start my training plan (that i created by myself...i’m always self coached)
column2: i’m incorporating weight training a few times a week. i’m not looking to add bulk (except maybe in the booty 🙊😂) because my body naturally takes on muscle fast and this year is more about endurance than bulk muscles. but strength is key to prevent injury. .

column1: i will be doing high reps and low weights throughout this training cycle. i’ll still incorporate all my favorite weight lifting just doing it in a different way. i’ll also be using my yoga practice and aerial fitness classes as my strength training 🤸🏽‍♂️
wide arm and close grip assisted pull-ups

i did a bit of everything today but will likely break up lower/upper body as i begin more focused training next week. or maybe 3-20 minute sessions each week. i’m flexible with my training as long as i get the work done each week!
feels so damn good to be back at it. and like really back at it. mind body spirit. i haven’t felt this alive
column3: excited and resolved in over a year!!!!!! it’s just freaking time to feel alive again! thank you himalaya mountains for healing my heart and spirit and reenergizing my body.

column2: i’m incorporating weight training a few times a week. i’m not looking to add bulk (except maybe in the booty 🙊😂) because my body naturally takes on muscle fast and this year is more about endurance than bulk muscles. but strength is key to prevent injury. .

column1: i will be doing high reps and low weights throughout this training cycle. i’ll still incorporate all my favorite weight lifting just doing it in a different way. i’ll also be using my yoga practice and aerial fitness classes as my strength training 🤸🏽‍♂️
wide arm and close grip assisted pull-ups

i did a bit of everything today but will likely break up lower/upper body as i begin more focused training next week. or maybe 3-20 minute sessions each week. i’m flexible with my training as long as i get the work done each week!
feels so damn good to be back at it. and like really back at it. mind body spirit. i haven’t felt this alive
column3: excited and resolved in over a year!!!!!! it’s just freaking time to feel alive again! thank you himalaya mountains for healing my heart and spirit and reenergizing my body.

column1: gabrielle senza: making the invisible visible. ⠀
in an era long before the #metoo movement
column3: the power of telling one's story publicly. her socially engaged projects empower participants to do that in safe and anonymous ways
column4: using art to empower and uplift their voices for others to hear. sharing their stories and vulnerability is healing and works to connect us to our humanity. the overarching theme running through her art is the desire to make the invisible visible. she loves art that makes you question what it is you're looking at and has a way of playing with your senses and challenging your expectations.⠀

column1: sony music has reportedly decided to part ways with r. kelly
column2: according to variety. a source said there isn’t any plans of any announcements being made in the near future. kelly is still listed on the website
column3: but the source said that there won’t be any indications about his departure from the label. his back catalog will still belong to rca and their parent company

column2: protests have been staged at sony’s new york headquarters. at sony music’s l.a. office
column3: a plane was hired by ultraviolet to fly above the office with a sign that read
column4: “rca/sony: drop sexual predator r. kelly.” rca’s stood by kelly throughout all of the allegations. according to sources
column5: it’s because he was never convicted of any crimes. however
column6: entertainment lawyer leslie frank said that major-label contracts have provisions that state if an artist is “convicted of a felony or a crime of moral turpitude
column7: generally speaking it is the label’s right to terminate the contract.” however
column8: kellz has yet to be found guilty of any of the allegations against him. “any record company — or
column10: any party to any contract — can decide they no longer want to be in the contract
column11: ” frank continued. “the question is what can happen as a result of them asserting their desire to terminate the term of the agreement. r. kelly could sue for damages. if r. kelly does not want to terminate the agreement and instigates a dispute saying that it’s a breach of contract by rca
column12: if rca is concerned about the cost of litigation and how a court might decide

column1: we are beyond excited to once again host and organize the 3rd annual women's march on philadelphia on january 19th
column2: 2019. our theme this year is ""we shall be heard""!

column1: 🔊we shall be heard in our neighborhoods as we organize for action against gun violence
🔊we shall be heard in the workplace where we expect equal pay for equal work and say #timesup to sexual harassment and assault.
🔊we shall be heard by the politicians who represent us on women's reproductive rights including safe and legal abortion
column5: a pathway to citizenship and immigration reform
column6: protection for the right and the ability for all citizens to vote and climate change policy.

column1: 🔊we hope that you will join us at 10am at eakins oval as we march down the ben franklin parkway to the philadelphia art museum where we will rally with a list of amazing speakers that represent all that we are fighting for.
🔊with only a few weeks to go
column2: we cannot do this without your help! our organization is an all volunteer board that is dedicated to these causes and donates our time to the planning and execution of this amazing event. donations are needed to pay for all of the various vendors for the event including sound

column9: 000. if everyone who’s attended the march donates $5 we will meet our goal! thank you for your support!🙏🏾

column1: survivors by and large are not believed.
who was treated with more dignity though?

now you can try to say it was because of the #metoo climate... but that’s underplaying the way antiblackness has been structured into every aspect of life & deeply socialized. it’s also ignoring the work black women did to try to get support for anita hill
that’s just one of the most popular instances that immediately come to mind due to recent events. the thousands of cases that are treated the exact same way show this problem is systemic.

for every black woman that reports 15 do not. by 18 around 60% of black girls have been sexually abused. trans women of color - particularly black women are targeted to the point their life expectancy has dropped to 35. the number of womxn in prisons is constituted mostly of abuse survivors and woc with estimates as high as 90% and 2/3 respectively.  largely because woc face more criminalization for their trauma and self defense - think of the thousands of womxn in cyntoia brown and chrystul kizer’s shoes.
this problem is all too real and i’m sick of watching people
column3: act like all survivors experience the same reality. i think people just don’t show up for black womxn

column1: this is why the best thing we can do as white or white passing women is give our love
column6: our money to the survivors in our lives who are treated with even less dignity. who are believed less

column3: and afab people. we must foster a catharsis from this. we must acknowledge the deep pain and then find healing. actually create communities of support. there’s got to be something after digging up the pain or we fester in it. i know

column1: 70904;instagram;2019-01-18 18:30:38;TRUE;;"thank you @amitaswadhin/ @mirror.memoirs! i am thrilled to share the creating change 2019 plenary stage with sibling child sexual abuse survivor-activists amita
i’m excited to share that @mirror.memoirs is part of three events at creating change 2019 (the annual conference by @thetaskforce )
for lgbtqi+ black and indigenous people and other people of color who have survived child sexual abuse. .
i’ll be moderating a panel featuring @afrolez
column4: all of whom are lgbtqi+ people of color who survived child sexual abuse and who have spent years working to end sexual violence. i am so blessed to call these incredible people my friends and comrades!

column1: i’ll be co-facilitating a sacred space for black and indigenous people and other people of color who survived any form of sexual violence. we will engage in open dialogue
column3: and visioning the path to a world without rape. survivors will learn about projects using storytelling and transformative justice as healing and preventative interventions that do not rely on police or prisons. .

column1: please spread the word to folks attending creating change!
and let me know in the comments if you’ll be at any of these sessions
column2: and if you have any specific topics you’d like to see discussed/addressed. 💜

column1: 70950;instagram;2019-01-18 17:10:24;FALSE;"join the women’s march 2019 tomorrow!!! join the #resistance
for all those attending a march tomorrow; be safe and stick a buddy or a group of friends.
additional info can be found in the link in my bio for all you need to know.

the women’s march is not just for women! being a #feminist does not make you less of a man. being part of the women’s march does not put your masculinity at risk! it makes you more of a man and shows that your masculinity is not toxic!
to be a feminist is to be a decent human being.
for all those who cannot march or who are marching
column2: this is not the end all be all! you must keep fighting! if nothing else
column3: call/write your senators and congress people who represent your district and

column2: tell them that the current status of the government (and world) is unacceptable and you will not stand for it.  do not rely on others to do this for you. the more people that contact the leaders in our government
column3: the more they will have to listen to the complaints of the people they represent (if they are following their duties as civil servants). don’t know your senators or congresspeople? there are websites on google that help you identify the names of the senators and congresspeople that represent your district/county and state if you’re located in the usa (i don’t know about internationally though
column4: sorry).... you have no excuse not to contact and complain to your senators and congresspeople if you are angry about where our government is in america.
